\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2303636 26 April, 1943
\par 
\par Subject: Morale Report for the Period 18 to 25 April, 1943.
\par 
\par To: Commanding General, NATOUSA, APO 512, U.S. Army.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16461592 1. HEALTH
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2303636 95% of the letters read state or indicate that excellent health prevails in this area, and that troops are in better physical condition than heretofore. Patients in hospitals continue to refer to excell
ent care and treatment though complaining that transportation from forward areas is rough and painful. The prevalence of veneral disease is still being commented on. A few medical officers are quite concerned ove
r the possibilities of epidemics during the coming warm weather. The following excerpts are from letters examined this past week:
\par 
\par "I can truthfully say that I'm in better health and in better health and in better physical condition than I've ever been in in my life." (20th Air Depot Group, APO 528-3).
\par 
\par ". . .we have had very little sickness so far. Especially considering the men sleep on the ground or the tile floors. Most are in holes in the ground but quite accustomed." (727 By. Oper. Bn., APO 302).
\par 
\par "Writing you and letting you know I'm feeling fine and in good shape." (4.32 CA Bn., APO 302).
\par 
\par "The shoulder isn't bad honey, so don't worry: They operated and removed the shell fragment. Was hit April 8 and reached here two days later. The 
worst part was the damn rough ride back out of the lines. I'm OK now and should be out of here in a couple more weeks. (58 Armd FA Bn., ADO ).
\par 
\par "My radio operator is laid up with a veneral disease of which there is an abundance here." (320 B. Group, 443rd B. Sq., APO 520).
\par 
\par "Wounds easily become infected here and there are lots of boils to treat for some reason." (1st Arm'd Div. APO 251).
\par 
\par "The weather is starting to approach my former concept of African climate. I can foresee some real hot, mug
gy weather. Personally I can tolerate it, but the accompanying diseases it may bring can incapacitate whole armies with one big, mighty, decisive blow--no war machine in the world can be so deadly nor so ruthless--even mighty Hitler's, or Stalin's. The tw
o big diseases in}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15353821  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2303636 humble on}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15353821  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2303636 
that will take its share along with Hitler of the "flower" of our Army will be (1) Dysentery and (2) Malaria. Both conditions are too glibly passed over as easy to prevent by certain prophylactic and ordered control measures. Whe
n men are on the battle field, practically speaking these two diseases are extremely difficult to control. When Army circular letters spout out this and that measure, it makes me smile. I picture some fool behind a comfortable desk, so remotely from my pr
o
blems as a Bn "Aid Man", that the measures so stated are much too impossible to exercise. In all these circulars they plead to me as a "Doctor" to help at all other times I'm considered an officer. What is particularly disgusting is their call to us in th
e
 name of "patriotism" and "the high standard of American Medicine."--You can now play the 'Stars and Stripes'. As a country doctor I had more facilities to investigate and control these diseases than the Army. I had a militant and genuinely interested Pub
lic Health Service at my disposal. These methods have been time tried by 1000's of doctors in practice, and yet the Army has failed to use them. Even suggestions and recommendations have been made to improve the inadequacy; but\'85
 An Epidemic will bring about the changes--but it will also be costly and involve loss of life. In these times human beings are worth so little." (Hq. Co. APO ).
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5906035 2. MAIL
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2303636 That there is an improvement in the mail service is indicat
ed by the decrease in unfavorable comments. Less than 50% of the comments during the past week have been unfavorable. There have been many references to the speed with which the mail 
arrives, some of it taking less than 10 days. Now that "V" mail is being photographed, there are many comments of dissatisfaction, the majority of complaints being that the "V" mail limits the size of the letter. The following comments are typical.
\par 
\par ".
 . .the best part of it all, is that it took only about 10 or 12 days for the whole batch to get across. They surely have done something to the mail service between here and home that makes life a lot more bearable for this Yankee." (Civil Affairs Sect., 
APO 512).
\par 
\par "I certainly have to hand it to the mail service--no matter where we are in these wild hills the mail gets here with very little delay." (Hq. 3rd Air Defense Wing, APO 525).
\par 
\par "Mail is coming through fine. Every few days I get a few letters. (Med. Det., 1880 Ord. Bn., APO 302).
\par 
\par "I should think that you would know our postal handicaps by now. Seriously though, our service is about a thousand percent up and I hope that yours is to." (XII Air Support Com APO 776).
\par 
\par "Your letter of April let reached me on April 10 and believe you me that is some service, considering where I am. It is a long and difficult journey from us to an APO. I feel encouraged over the mail service." (Hq. 34th Div., APO 34.).
\par 
\par "Just got a cable you sent to London on Dec. 6th!! Also, on the same day, I got a letter you wrote on Feb. 24.th!!! This mail service makes one think of how nice it would be to be over in India--or maybe Siam." (34th Service Group, APO 762).
\par 
\par "For some uncanny reason there have been s
everal who have deemed it more advisable to forward my mail from my former station to my present station in another part of North Africa by way of the states so that there will be a mere matter of another six weeks or so tacked on to the ordinary time bef
ore I will have an opportunity to get caught up on the 'news'." (Signal Section, Force Hq., APO 512).
\par 
\par "Plenty of room on the ships for clothes and food for the Arabs but not for our letters packages and food--this whole damned lend-lease proposition is a farce in the way they work it. Stuff is sold here cheaper than in the U.S." (6th Arm'd Inf., APO 251).

\par 
\par "It seems funny when you think about this mail being 4. weeks old. It sure is good when it gets here, but the service they talk about in the magazines and newspapers in the States certainly isn't working out here." (12th A.F. APO 650).
\par 
\par "We have been notified that V-mail is now the only type of mail that is guaranteed air mail. I think that it is a hell of a note when the Nation cannot provide 
adequate mail service for the men who are over here fighting and dying." (6th Armd Inf., APO 251).
\par 
\par "They've told us that V-mail is the only kind of mail that will be flown back to the States. Personally I don't like it at all, either on the sending or
 receiving end. When I write a letter I like to write until I run out and then quit. With that damned V-mail, unless one has a typewriter, one can hardly get started before he is out of paper and has to stop. Exasperating! Even if one only has just a page
 to write the limitation still induces that confined feeling. I don't see why they should insist on V-mail here when they don't even have micro-film equipment as yet." (82nd Bomb Sq., 12th B.G., APO 785).
\par 
\par "The V-mail you wrote Feb. 7th got here March 9
th and the letter of same date got here April 19th but I would rather have the letters. I know that V mail is encouraged. I have talked with the general in charge of the army postal service and he is sold on V-mail but the soldier isn't. One now and then 
is OK." (Hq. 34th Div., APO 34.).
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5906035 3. TRAINING
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2303636 There are few comments on training, the majority of these are critical of the training received in the States. The following comments have been noted.
\par 
\par "I am afraid that what we have missed most in our hectic training is first: the development of a real discipline. There has been too much molly-coddling and evasion of the point. Responsibility for this rests fairly close to the roof. Secondly the va
st majority of our new officers and many of our older ones have absolutely no sense of responsibility." (168th Inf., AFO 34).
\par 
\par "And although I think Barksdale and its training program were, are, and always will be, way off the beam--I feel as though I am ready for combat." (320 Bomb Gr., APO 520).
\par 
\par "They shouldn't let anyone in the States get to be more than a first lieutenant. As a major with a hell of a lot of knowledge that most of the lads didn't have, I'm practically worthless until I get some 
combat background. All of these kids popping loose over here ought to be reduced to shave tails. This goes for a lot of colonels also." (47th Bomb Gr., AAF, APO 762).
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5906035 4. EQUIPMENT
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2303636 Over 90% of the references to equipment have been favorable. Comment f
rom Air Corps personnel have consistently praised the "Spitfire", and many of the fliers prefer that ship. There has been some favorable references to our machine guns and artillery. The following comments are from letters examined:
\par 
\par "It sure amazed me when I noticed the difference of the American Soldier from the English, French, Italians and the rest. Our equipment and the way we handle it is so very far above there\rquote 
s no doubt in my mind who has the best army in the world. The moral here is very high and everyone think the world of us, even the Italian prisoners." (2004. Pipe Line Co. (Sep), APO 763).
\par 
\par "Boy, I'm glad I'm flying 'Spitfires'--they are plenty good and one need not fear the Messerchmitt and Fock Wulf in them, if you fly with caution and keep alert." (4th Fighter Sq., 52nd Ftr. Gr., APO 525).
\par 
\par "The Dutchmen are more afraid of our machine guns than any other weapon we have." (209 CA (AA) APO 700).
\par 
\par "Nellie we are taking up everything right now but the equipment the men have on
 their backs and their blankets. They tell us we are not going to draw cotton clothing and that will leave them with one set of woolens. Where we are going or what will happen to us no one knows." (168th Inf. A10 34).
\par 
\par "We are very well taken care of t
hough. We have the best of equipment, and never once that I can remember have I gone hungry or been cold through lack of warm clothes. We also have the best in weapons and beaucoup ammunition and so forth. In spite of the fact that we are in a filthy coun
try where sanitation is unheard of, our health is excellent." (175th FA).
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5906035 5. RATIONS
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2303636 Approximately 80% of references to rations are favorable, the most consistent complaint being lack of fresh meat, and lack of variety. There was one comment on German
 rations which may be of interest. In some units there is still a feeling of discontent over the shortage of PX supplies. The following comments are typical.
\par 
\par "Just to make you jealous, I'll tell you what I had for breakfast this morning. Breakfast is always our best meal and our cooks do a wonderful jab under conditions you cannot possibly imagine." (84th FA Bn., APO 9).
\par 
\par "We had fresh meat last night. The mess officers had it barbecued and boy was it good." (321 Bomb Gr.).
\par 
\par "But we do very well over here and have no need to complain." (412 Signal Co., AMU, APO 650).
\par 
\par "A few days ago they took all the E.M. away from the officers mess and installed French waiters. The head waiter was formerly the head waiter on the Normandy, he acts the part
 but it is rather hard to complete the picture on "C" rations. The addition of a bottle of wine helps him complete the former atmosphere however. We generally eat well over here, much better than the civilians back in the states. I understand now that we 
are on American rations instead of British, we rather enjoy the meals." (G-4 Sec. Force Hq., APO 512).
\par 
\par "Are you really interested in our food? Today at noon we had salmon croquettes, spinach, hominy, lemonade (artificial) bread and peanut butter. The o
ther day the officers bought a couple of tough bulls, and for two days we had steak, hamburger and meatloaf. Usually everything comes out of cans, except pancakes for breakfast occasionally." (310th Bomb Grp. APO 520).
\par 
\par "The food is pretty good now if you want to call it that. It's still all canned. I never want to see another can of spam as long as I live. Leave it to the Americans to overdo things. In the last war it was beans. This time it's spam." (16th Troop carr
ier SO., APO 650).
\par 
\par "We do enjoy reading some of the adds that come out at home though in the magazines. One good one tells all about the wonderful butter that some mfgr. developed for the army that wouldn't melt in the hottest African sun and kept so
 well. Well he is right about it not melting, also about the damn stuff not spoiling or rather keeping so long. The reason it keeps so long is because no one will eat it. It\rquote 
s so full of preservation or wax that it is about like eating wax with oil, spam is swell stuff but not three times a day. Another joke is the fresh beef quest
ion. When we first got over here we were told we couldn't have it because it all went to the troops at the front. Well the closer you get to the front the less you see of it. In
 fact we have had none since we have been up here." (G-3 Sec., Hq. 9th Inf. Div.).
\par 
\par "The only thing I can't possibly stand is the food here. It's the most sorry food that I have ever tried to eat or ever hope to put in my mouth. I very seldom eat a mea
l here. Most of us are buying eggs and fruit from the natives and are making out okay. It isn't the best diet in the world but we get along on it," (97 Bomb Grp. APO 520).
\par 
\par "The other day we got hold of some German rations, which they abandoned when th
ey ran off, and it sure was lots better than ours. Of course, a good deal of it came from the occupied countries, as indicated by the labels on the cans." (6th Armd Inf., APO 251).
\par 
\par "Things like cigars and candy are mostly out with us, for they have to be saved for you jerks back home. I suppose that you get what you want at the PX. You should see our PX. You\rquote re lucky if you can get shoo gum here." (379 Bomb Sq. APO 520).

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5906035 6. ENTERTAINMENT
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2303636 All comments on this subject have been favorable. The syste
m of routing motion picture shows, bands and entertainers to various units is being received with much enthusiasm. Comments on the special service section, and especially of the Red Cross have been exceptionally praiseworthy. The following are some of the
 comments that have been noted.
\par 
\par "The shows we have had here are all good and there are a good many of them." (III Air Service Area Command, APO 528).
\par 
\par "Wish you were here tonight. They have a visiting band here and they are playing a short ways up the way. . . I guess we can't complain over here because we have a show about once a week and a band every .Friday." (310 Bomb Grp., APO 520).
\par 
\par "Right now they are playing a band outside. Oh! Yes! We get some entertainment, and occasionally we get movies, so you see we don't do so badly." (379 Bomb Sqdn., APO 520).
\par 
\par "It is getting better over here all the time. We do have lots of fun when we get to town. We see shows now not so new though." (02 CA Bn., APO 302).
\par 
\par "The best entertainment and rec
reation for the boys overseas are radios and special service movies which are shown from unit to unit. Last night we invited 100 boys of the 713th Op. Bn. to our Co. and we saw the movie "Wake Island." Included were a news reel and an added subject. The S
pecial Service operator played recordings of the well-known dance bands. You should have seen the boys in the courtyard jitterbugging with one another. All enjoyed the program thoroughly." (703rd Ry. Grand Div., APO 529).
\par 
\par "I haven't run across a Red Cross Club yet that wasn't a success. My thanks and congratulations and the thanks of an officer for the wonderful way in which the A.R.C. takes care of the social and personal affairs of our G.I.'s." (751 Tank Bn., APO 302).

\par 
\par "The Red Cross have started
 serving us donuts and coffee when we come back from flying. The Red Cross is really doing a swell job over here. They put on good movies for us set up day rooms for the enlisted men with radios, games, food and other entertainments and in big towns have 
service clubs where the men can eat and sleep and have a place to hang out. With the few workers over here at present they can't be praised too highly." (34.2 Bomb Sq., APO 52A).
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5906035 7. SPORTS
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2303636 It is evident that athletic activities are being fostered in m
any units where they receive favorable response. The sports that seem to predominate are baseball, soft ball and volley ball. All comments on sports have been favorable.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5906035  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2303636 "We have a very good softball team here in the company and have played quite a few games." (244 QM Bn.).
\par 
\par "I have been getting a little exercise these days. We had a baseball tournament and I am patching for the Hq. team. We were beaten in the Semi-finals, but we did have a lot of fun." (310 Bomber Grp. APO 520).
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5906035 8. LEAVE
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2303636 References to going back to the States at the completion of the African campaign continue to prevail in the theatre as shown by the following comments:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2303636 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5906035 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2303636 "It's OVER and I'm OK--It's OVER! The African campaign is over for us, darling! Our jo
b is done. . .As for my coming home now that our job here is finished, we should know for sure about this before the end of this month. It does seem quite likely that we shall, however. Perhaps I'll be walking in on you within two weeks or so after you ge
t this! I pray so !!!" (135 Inf. APO 34).
\par 
\par "Read in the Stars and Stripes that all American troops would return to the States after this African battle, which shouldn't be very long." (813th T. D. Bn., APO 302).
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5906035 9. QUARTERS
\par 
