\par 13. HOME AFFAIRS: Letters continue to refer to strikes and labor trouble in the States in no uncertain terms and indications are that the American soldier is much concerned in such matters. Advice against joining the WAACs or similar organizations are
 still noted in letters. The following comments are typical.
\par "The days and nights of constant flirting with death nearly dive me crazy though. Too bad a lot of our union leaders and workers in plants at home couldn't be brought over here for a few week
s of it. The loafing on the jobs, the strikes, the wasting of valuable time would immediately cease. If they only knew how many more lives they are costing because of lack of proper equipment ETC. such laggardism would cease. A few bombs dropped at home w
ould help a lot in the opinion of most of us. It makes me bitter when you see a man\rquote s head shot off, or another\rquote s arm fly 30 feet in the air or another\rquote 
s body blown to bits as I have seen and at home they have to beg them to stay on the job or pay three tim
es what they are worth. And you have to join a union in order to work and pay dues whether you want to or not. What a racket, I wonder what we are fighting for sometimes." (9th Inf. Div., APO 9).
\par 
\par "One of the fellows just got a copy of the time magazin
e--and it gives the story of the Boeing factory going out on strike--the dirty no good bastards--and that's mild. They should draft every one of the sons of bitches and send them to Guadacanal or out here in Africa--what the hell kind of country am I figh
ting for anyway? Why don't those people who don't like their "working conditions" or "wage scales" come out here and look at ours--if you\rquote 
re to be paid by the amount of effort you put out--there isn't enough money in the U.S. to pay off the kid who gets a G
erman flame-thrower in his face--or a tank cutting him in two or the crew of a ship diving in to hit nose on at 400 miles an hour. What type of stinker do we have exempted from the draft to draw fabulous wages in defense industry and then stop producing e
v
en for one minute the stuff that keeps us alive out here? I hear that Eddie Rickenbacker told them off once and got nailed for it--they ought to give 'Rick' a medal and a good platoon of combat men and the job of working over those snotnosed leeches in 'd
efense work. How can you expect us to do the job of dying like men for democracy if that democracy operates at home like an old maid trying to mother a dead end kid?" (XII Bomber Command, APO 520).
\par 
\par "Since I have been up I have seen some fireworks. And
 I'm glad of it. People back home don't seem to realize a war is on it seems. Arguing about little petty things that sometimes don't amount to a hill of beans. Up front it is different. Almost everyone cooperates with each other." (1979 QM Co. APO 528).

\par 
\par "From your letters I see that you are very busy with your work-a work of great importance in the war effort. Sailors and soldiers have to be clothed, and you are helping to do this, and I can well understand your interest in your work. In this great st
ruggle which engulfs the entire world, every worthwhile person is doing and wants to do his part. Who knows better than I, that our enemy is a brutal one, who would have the greater part of the world under his hell if he could." (1st Eng. Bn., APO 1).

\par 
\par "And this stuff you have been mentioning about the WAACs is really funny to worry about. If there is one thing I will not allow is that. I and most of the boys over here consider them quite the laughing stock of the Nation and all of us think they stink."
 (355th CA Bn., APO 700).
\par 
\par "Now don't go joining the WAACa or you'll be in for a 'whack' from yours truly." (13th A.R., APO 251).
