\par 15. RELATIONS WITH THE ALLIED TROOPS}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5906035 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2303636 All references to the allied troops are favorable. The American soldier has the utmost respect and feeling of fr
iendliness for the British soldier. Many writers state that their opinion of the British has radically changed since they have come in contact with him. Expressions from British and French troops whose mail passes through this office also reflects the fav
orable relationships between the different forces. The following are only a few of the comments that have been noted.
\par 
\par "There is, however, one statement that I want to go on record now and it concerns the British officers and soldiers. The adverse criti
cism that is heard in the States of the English soldiers is pure Axis bull. I have met hundreds of them personally and they are fine fellows, excellent soldiers and first class fighting men. The only trouble is that there is not enough of them. In the pas
t the enemy had them outnumbered. It is certainly gratifying to see our men and the English getting along so well together. They are real comrades-in-arms. With great respect for each other\rquote 
s good qualities. . . . every last private who has come in contact with the British troops will tell you the same thing." (753rd Ry. Shop Bn., APO 700).
\par 
\par "The English armies are wonderful and they know their business and can really use everything they have and we have given them. The 1st and 8th Army are on the ball and Montgomery and Alexander are really men of the battle." (1st Engr. Bn., APO 1).
\par 
\par "I myself, am very proud to work with the British Army they are a real bunch of good fellows and hard fighters--and it is my personal belief that we two can whip the daylights out of the Hun--yes sir!! The British and American armies can't be stopped."
 (813 TD Bn., APO 302).
\par 
\par "I don't care what one says about the British, the Tommy over here is all right for my money and I think that every American that has had contact with them over here feels the same way. They work like hell, have very little and
 make damn good soldiers and there seems to be no limit to the length he will go out of his way to help the American and the boys at the front say he is a damn tough fighter. (310 Service Gp. APO 762).
\par 
\par "If anybody tells you that the British and Americans don't get along--they're crazy. We may not agree on a few things but its sure been a mutual feeling of respect and being damn glad to see each other over here." (1st Armd Regt. APO 251).
\par 
\par "The news from the other parts of the field has been good as
 old man Montgomery seems to have Rommel on the run for sure this time and personally he can keep right on the job. He's the best man there is for my money. I'll be quite frank with you and say that when I was back in England I didn't have such a good opi
nion of the English, but when you fight with them, and next to them, they are really all right. They can surely fight, and they can take it, much better sometimes, I think than we." (135th Inf., APO 34).
\par 
\par "My hat is off to the British Army. They are real fighting men and I doubt that we could have done what they have done." (Hq Div. Arty., APO 34).
\par 
\par "And let me tell you, the British are no slouches either. A better bunch of fellows I've never seen. They're really tops with all of us. The Tommies and Yanks get along like brothers. (AT Co. 135th Inf., APO 34).
\par 
\par "There is profound admiration for the British in the old gang, since we have seen them in operation. They've really got what it takes, and I believe that everyone here would take off their hats to them. (Hq. 2nd Bn., APO 34.).
\par 
\par "I don't know whether you notice that I am using a lot of American expressions in my letters to you but I'm mixing with the Yanks all day and I guess I can't help talking like they do. They are a hell of a good bunc
h of lads and we get on very well." (7 A.A. S.C., APO 330).
\par 
\par "We have some exceptionally delightful Americans to work with. They are really charming. The tripe that people talk about Americans-I've met dozens and haven't encountered a loud one yet alt
hough I'm not saying they don't exist. You should hear them talk about the Eighth Army and our performance generally in this war. It makes one glow with pleasure." (B.N.A.F.). (letter is written by a French soldier attached to the U.S. Army).
\par 
\par "I can t
ell you at once that Americans are very congenial and that they did not come with empty hands. Their food, for instance, is not levied in Africa. Quite the opposite, they are bringing quite large quantities of provisions for the civilian population." (no 
address given).
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5906035 16. CENSORSHIP
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2303636 
During the past week a total of 17 Form 912's for censorship violations were sent out, 12 of which were on officers, 3 on enlisted men, and 2 on civilians attached to the army. In addition there were also 319 pieces of m
ail returned for violations that did not warrant a Form 912. Most of these were due to local money being sent to the States, for sending postcards with geographical locations printed thereon, and for violations of regulations on the use of blue envelopes.
 Comments on censorship are 90% unfavorable. Military personnel consider the censorship regulations too severe, and complain that it limits them in writing interesting letters. There are also comments about the censors holding and delaying mail. The rec
ords will show that mail is not held up over 24 hours for censorship purposes. References in a few units indicate that the new censorship regulations have not been described to them. A few writers, mostly officers, intimate that they have prearranged code
s. The mail of such is being watched very carefully. The following comments were noted.
\par 
\par "Was in a swell town yesterday and wish the censors were not so peculiar--so that I could write about it. The papers tell all about the town, as far as the fightin
g is concerned but I am not allowed to tell of my being there! Funny stuff, this Army--isn't it, Mr. Censor?" (Hq. II Corps, APO 302).
\par 
\par "As the censor gets stricter and stricter I am afraid my letters will get duller and duller until I am reduced to describing only the food and the sunshine." (149 WAAC Post BA., APO 512).
\par 
\par "There is so little to write--censorship is very strict and I certainly don't want to violate it in any way." (73rd Sta. Hosp, APO 700).
\par 
\par "We have a batch of new censorship rules that makes it next to impossible to write an interesting letter." (APO 528).
\par 
\par "If you were to read the letter, you would never realize that it contained military information and it was not until the Censor pointed out to me what was wrong with it, that I realized. It\rquote 
s really wonderful how they can piece together a letter and get so much out of it." (Hq. Sq., 5th Wing (US) APO 520).
\par 
\par "The other about Censorship was published in Yank Magazine. True enough, too, but very necessary, it Should be more strict. Would be very interested to know who the fellows are that paint such be
autiful word pictures and tell you all so much." (209 CA (AA), APO 700).
\par 
\par "I think a lot of our mail is being delayed on account of very poor handling by Chief Base Censor--everyone has the same trouble but such is the Army." (713 Ry. Op. Bn., APO 763).
\par 
\par "That reminds me, you said something about British mail getting here in only two weeks. That's really swell but some of your letters are in the Censor's office nearly that long. No foolin', its true and it makes me burn. I\rquote 
m all for censorship because it is necessary but when it means that much of a delay, I think it\rquote s pretty bad. Here\rquote 
s one dated March 25th and postmarked April 8, another dated April 1, postmarked April 11th. I'll be damned if that doesn't go against the grain." (34th C.A. Brigade (AA), APO 529).
\par 
\par "Honey you keep on saying you\rquote re not getting letters from me. I can't understand it unless they are being held up by the Censors. I write every other day." (2nd. Sig. Co., AR) 528).
\par 
\par "I can't seem to get hold of a copy of the censorship regs for intra theatre correspondence, but I imagine they are amply ridiculous." (321 Bomb Gp., APO 520).
\par 
\par "Darling, until I tell you different, there isn't any use in using the plan we talked of about writing in because I have told you every bit 
throu repition if you know what I mean, as I could have that way. What I have kept repeating is supposed to be OK with the spot check censors, but if there comes a time when I can't say something in that manner, then I will use our plan. I will let you kn
ow when I am using it though. Please let me know if any of my letters happen to be spot-checked and anything is cut out." (312th Ord. Bn., APO 700).
\par 
