\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2303636 About 5% of the mail examined contain complaints of a general nature. Complaint
s of non-receipt of allotments and safe arrival cards being most consistent. Other complaints prominent this week include (1) lack of promotions, (2) individual dislike or lack of faith in superior officers, (3) the employment of the same units in the cam
paign and (4)
\par inactivity.
\par 
\par "I can't understand why Max didn't get that allotment yet I am going to try and find out why if I can." (2639 QM Truck Bn., APO 763).
\par 
\par "Wish I knew a Newspaper reporter or two. A write-up in the papers about the soldiers o
verseas not receiving any allotments, after the soldier had made out one, and in some instances like mine for a period of eight months, would not look so good, But I can't write anything like that to the papers nor can I write to a Congressman for assista
nce, but the parents of the selectees can write to the Congressman because their sons don't get mail within the time they think they should." (1st Armd Div. APO 251).
\par 
\par "Please keep check on my allotment and let me know if on April 1st a check for $175.00 was sent." (30th Inf. APO 3).
\par 
\par "I guess they have them pretty well messed up and the men do not like it so very well. It is difficult to persuade them to buy bonds." (899th TD Bn., APO 302).
\par 
\par "I filled out several cards that were to be mailed whe
n we arrived here. They were supposed to announce my safe arrival and give my address. Evidently they weren't mailed because you never got it and Aunt Anne in Chicago never got the one I filled out for her. I sent one to Sam also but I don't know if he go
t his or not." (321st, Bomb Group, APO 520).}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15353821  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2303636 
\par 
\par "Guess you are getting tired of hearing me gripe all the time but it just isn't fair. Clark Gable is now a Capt. in the Air Corps. he was in the class after me. I just can't figure it out. The boys in the S
tates are surely riding the gravy train, while we are sweating it out over here. There is liable to be a rebellion if something isn't done for the boys over here who are doing the dirty work and not getting the promotions." (81st Ftr. Gp. 93rd Ftr. Sq., A
PO 762).
\par 
\par "Sometime I wish I was in the navy I might get some place." (87 Ord. Co. APO 668).}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2303636 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5906035 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2303636 "So many of the brass hats seem to be concerned with promotions to the extent that the fellow who is really carrying the load is often not thought of." (Provost Marshall Gen. Office, APO 512).
\par 
\par "I wish they would give these other people a chance to fight this war instead of using one division." (26th Inf. APO 1).
\par 
\par "If I were in a complaining mood, there are plenty of other more important things that I could kick about, but I won't. I'll only say that the proud records of American Generalship, that w
as inaugurated in the Civil War, is certainly continuing. I think I'll be a Republican from now on." (6th Armd Inf., APO 251).
\par 
\par "This business is OK for a little while, BUT IT gets old after so long. It seems though that the big boys sitting around th
e H.Q. offices have determined that the pilots of this day and age can stand a lot more than they once thought they could. This is a very grave}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5906035  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2303636 
mistake though believe me." (12th Bomb Grp., APO 785).
\par 
\par "There seems to be a mistaken idea that there is nob
ody else in this G.D. army and war except the good old and tired 26 inf. That is not censorable. Before we moved in one of the officers expressed the same opinion in the presence of members of the staff. They only glared." (26 Inf., APO ).
\par 
\par "I wish the U.S. Army would find out it has 5,000,000 other soldiers to play around with. It seems he is using about 3 divisions, one of these three divisions all the time to do everything an army should be doing." (1st Engr. Bn., APO 1).
\par 
\par "It makes me so mad to 
know that we are sitting here doing absolutely nothing. It isn't just that I want to see tragic and horrible things- my curiosity is not that morbid, but if there are such conditions, we want to work also. If I thought that I could do any better by transf
e
rring, I surely would, but my fate would probably be another do-nothing unit, and then I would really give up in despair. I'm so damned disgusted today, that I hate everyone, even myself. Do you mind my ranting? I can't somehow write to my friends at home
 about it. They try to sacrifice cheerfully to help us overseas, and its rather difficult to let them know that we are hardly worth it. I try to tell myself that it\rquote s like a dream that\rquote 
s been broken. Most of us had such illusions of the services we were going to do and it hurts, awfully, to admit to ourselves that we are taking it easy, when others are doing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5906035  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2303636 the work. (26th Gen. Hosp., APO 700).
\par 
\par "This place is becoming very dull and sure wish that we could}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15353821  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2303636 move on somewhere or do something different for a change." (85th QM Co., APO 302).
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5906035 1}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2303636 8. GENERAL}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5906035 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2303636 Though over 95 of the references show a very high moral, it is to be noted that comments now are being made to the effect that some writers are dissatisfied and want to be finished with the war. There 
have been an increasing number of uncomplimentary remarks about the WAACs in this theater, and there are comments written by a WAAC officer indicating that such remarks have gotten to the States. References to Axis personnel continue to indicate that the 
Italians are eager to surrender, and also an example of apparent sabotage in German munition factories.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2303636 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5906035 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2303636 "The morale of everyone is excellent and there are no words which can adequately describe the magnificent work which is being done by all." (20th Air Depot Gr., APO 528).
\par 
\par "The army is mine from now on out if I have anything to say about it. You will never see me join a union or go into a factory or die of starvation." (68 Armd. PA Bn., APO 251).
\par 
\par "We have been strafed and bombed, but the Luft
waffe is a weak sister. Their bombs do more ploughing of Arab fields than anything else. There are more cases in the hospital from Jeep accidents than from anything else. The boys here are shooting them down 3 and 4. to 1 all the time," (82 Fighter Contro
l Sect., APO 525).
\par 
\par "In the past I haven't had personal hatred for the Jerries, but rather a feeling that it was soldiers against soldiers in which each was fighting for what he thought was right. Within the past couple of weeks however I have received 
a couple of blows that have embittered me. Day before yesterday I lost a very close friend and a loyal follower. If I ever get the opportunities--and I will--I intend to get plenty of revenge for that blow." (18th Inf., APO 1).
\par 
\par "I know one thing for sure if I am away from you for another year, when I come back home I won't be normal, and you can write to your Congressman about that. And come to think of it, it wouldn't be such a bad idea if a lot of people wrote in and let it
 be known that they are fed up on this war business, and when I say business it seems to me and looks as if it is starting to be just that. Here, of late I have been reading some of the papers from the States, and the profits the manufacturers are making,
 I tell you I boil inside. This damn thing has gone far enough and it is up to the people at home to do a little hollering, and end this damn war." (2625 Sig. Ser. Reg., APO 512).
\par 
\par "If this war don't end soon I'll go crazy." (1st Gen. Depot, APO 698).
\par 
\par "Thus far I have been on twelve raids and the sooner this is over the better I will like it. I do navigating and bombarding and I have never in my life felt so damned naked as I do when sitting in the greenhouse and Jerry is throwing all manure of stuf
f at us." (12 Bomb Grp., APO 785).
\par 
\par "I overheard some conversation by a noisy group of them (WAACs) and their opinions in general seem to be that they wish to hell they were home where they belong. I wish for their sakes (and the army's too) that they were." (68th CA (AA), APO 668). 
\par 
\par "I am sure you will be able to control the publicity so it won't be as bad as ours. We have just heard that one of our company has broadcast from a hospital in the States about her experiences on the war over. I hope y
ou didn't hear her. Cannot imagine why she was allowed to speak. We tried to leave her behind as 'unfit for overseas duty' but were overruled. All in all we seem to be getting some pretty mean digs on all sides and families are writing that they hear we a
re to be sent home for bad behaviour. Considering how these girls are working and how well they are behaving under the most trying circumst
ances it is a little hard to take. Some of the stories about them come straight from Berlin." (149 WRAC Post Hq., APO 512).
\par 
\par "Yesterday I questioned two Italian prisoners, of the thousands which we have taken. The Italians don't want to go on fighting. They call to us and when we approach them they come out with their hands up. For example, one of our trucks was fill
ed with Italians when it roiled into a ditch. The American soldiers left to get help. These Italians, without any guard, started working on the truck, and after about a half hour, here came the truck, driven by a prisoner. They were all singing like crazy
 men. We never have to put them under guard, because we couldn't even drive them away by force. The Americans couldn't lose this war--they are too good. An Italian officer, from Rome, told me, 'Mussolini is a brigant who should have been assassin
ated.' I asked him 'Do you get along with the Germans ' - he replied-'How could we get along with those bastards? They want everything for themselves and don't give us anything to eat! Most of these Italians are Bersaglieri." (examiner\rquote 
s note- Bersaglieri- an Italian armored force). (6th Arend Inf., APO 251).
\par 
\par "Some time ago we took a lot of Italian prisoners and they said they were fed up with this war. The Italians are in a bad way, but believe me I don't sympathize with them at all. They can't believe that an
 American can speak Italian better than an Italian. I told them that I was glad that my parents knew enough to leave Italy years ago." (translation from Italian). (R.C.N. Co., 13th A.R., APO ).
